---
description: Docker, CI/CD, and AWS deployment rules for SalesIQ
globs: .github/**, docker-compose*.yml, backend/Dockerfile, frontend/Dockerfile
---

Deployment stack:
- Docker + Docker Compose (local development and staging)
- GitHub Actions (CI/CD pipelines)
- AWS (production: ECS/EKS, RDS PostgreSQL, ElastiCache Redis, S3, CloudFront, Secrets Manager)
- PostgreSQL 16 (managed via AWS RDS in production)
- Redis 7 (managed via AWS ElastiCache in production)

Docker rules:
- Backend Dockerfile: Python 3.12, multi-stage build (builder → runtime), non-root user.
- Frontend Dockerfile: Node 20, multi-stage build (deps → builder → runner), `next start` production server.
- Do not bake secrets into Docker images — pass via environment variables at runtime.
- Keep image sizes minimal — use `.dockerignore` to exclude dev deps, test files, local `.env`.
- All services in `docker-compose.yml` must have health checks defined.
- Service startup order: PostgreSQL → Redis → backend → Celery worker → frontend.

GitHub Actions CI rules (`.github/workflows/`):
- `ci-backend.yml`: lint (ruff) → type check (mypy) → pytest (with mocked external services) → build Docker image.
- `ci-frontend.yml`: lint (eslint) → type check (tsc --noEmit) → build (next build) → Vitest.
- All checks must pass before merge to `main` or `develop`.
- Use GitHub Actions secrets for CI credentials — never store in code.
- On push to `main`: run full CI + deploy to staging.
- On tagged release: deploy to production.

Environment management:
- Three environments: `development` (local Docker Compose), `staging` (AWS, mirrors prod), `production` (AWS).
- Each environment has its own `.env` or AWS Secrets Manager secret set.
- `backend/.env.example` and `frontend/.env.local.example` must always be up to date with all required variables.
- Never commit `.env`, `.env.local`, or any file containing actual secrets.

AWS production setup:
- Compute: Kubernetes / EKS (per CLAUDE.md infrastructure spec).
- Database: AWS RDS PostgreSQL 16 (multi-AZ for production).
- Cache: AWS ElastiCache Redis 7.
- Object storage: AWS S3 (call recordings, exports).
- CDN: AWS CloudFront (frontend static assets from Next.js build).
- Secrets: AWS Secrets Manager (all API keys, DB credentials, JWT secrets).
- Monitoring: Prometheus + Grafana (per CLAUDE.md); CloudWatch as secondary sink.

Backend health checks:
- `GET /health` — returns `{"status": "ok"}`, used by load balancer and container health checks.
- `GET /ready` — returns `{"status": "ready"}` when DB and Redis connections are alive.

Celery worker deployment:
- Run as a separate pod/container from the FastAPI API server.
- Scale Celery workers independently based on queue depth (e.g. auto-scale on `analysis` queue length).
- Use separate worker pools per queue: `transcription`, `analysis`, `prediction`, `notifications`.

Do not:
- Hardcode AWS resource IDs, region names, S3 bucket names, or RDS endpoints in application code — use env vars.
- Mix local-only Docker Compose hacks into production `Dockerfile` or application logic.
- Deploy to production without running full CI pipeline.
- Assume synchronous task processing scales — Celery workers must be horizontally scalable.
- Share environment-specific config between `development` and `production` environments.
